            <p title="About HTML and CSS" style="color: whitesmoke; font-weight: bold; text-align:center; padding-bottom: 0%;">OVERVIEW
            <hr>
                <abbr style="text-decoration: none;" title="Hypertext Markup Language">HTML</abbr> stands for <span class="assert">Hypertext Markup Language</span>. It is the standard markup language used for 
                creating and structuring web pages. HTML uses tags to mark elements within a document
                and provides the <span class="assert">structure and content of a webpage.</span>
                HTML documents are composed of a series of tags enclosed in angle brackets (<>). These
                tags define the elements of a webpage, such as headings, paragraphs, links, images, lists,
                tables, forms, and more. Each tag serves a specific purpose and has its own attributes and
                content.
            </p>
            <p>
                <hr>
                <abbr style="text-decoration: none;" title="Cascading Style Sheets 3">CSS3</abbr> is the latest version of the CSS language used to <span class="assert">define the
                presentation and styling of HTML documents.</span> It is an extension of the previous CSS2
                specification and introduces new features, capabilities, and improvements to enhance the
                design and layout of web pages.
                CSS3 includes a wide range of new selectors, properties, and modules that provide more
                control over the appearance and behavior of elements. Some key features introduced in
                CSS3 include:<br>
                <ol>
                    <li><span class="assert">Selectors</span>: CSS3 introduces advanced selectors that allow for more precise targeting of elements. This includes attribute selectors, structural pseudo-classes, and more.</li>
                    <li><span class="assert">Flexible Box Layout (Flexbox)</span>: CSS3 introduces a new layout module called Flexbox, which provides
                    a flexible way to create responsive and dynamic layouts, especially for building complex navigation
                    menus and flexible grid systems.</li>
                    <li><span class="assert">Grid Layout</span>: CSS3 Grid Layout is a powerful layout system that allows for creating two-dimensional
                    grid-based layouts. It enables more control over the placement and alignment of elements, making it
                    easier to design complex and responsive layouts.</li>
                    <li><span class="assert">Transitions and Animations</span>: CSS3 introduces properties like transition and animation, enabling the
                    creation of smooth transitions between states and the animation of elements, providing more interactivity
                    and engaging user experiences.</li>
                    <li><span class="assert">Transformations</span>: CSS3 introduces 2D and 3D transformations, such as scaling, rotating, skewing, and translating elements, allowing for creative and interactive effects.</li>
                    <li><span class="assert">Media Queries</span>: CSS3 enhances media queries, allowing for more targeted styling based on different device
                    characteristics, such as screen size, resolution, and orientation. This enables responsive web designing.</li>
                </ol><br>
                <q style="color: rgb(255, 208, 0);font-style: italic; padding-left: 20%;" title="Quote">Education without application is just entertainment</q>
            </p>
